{"title":"Cross-Modal Alignment via Variational Copula Modelling","domain":"MULTIMODAL","seeds":[{"problem":"Multimodal fusion often aligns heterogeneous modality embeddings (e.g., EHR, images, text) via concatenation or simple similarity losses, which fails to model complex cross-modal dependencies and can yield biased joint representations.","method":"CM2 introduces a copula-driven alignment that explicitly models the joint distribution of modality embeddings while learning flexible marginals. Each modality’s latent embedding is modeled with a K-component diagonal-covariance Gaussian mixture whose CDF F_m(z_m) is computed, and a parametric copula C (e.g., Gumbel, Frank, Gaussian) with learnable parameter α couples the marginals to form the joint C(F_1(z_1),…,F_M(z_M)). Training maximizes an ELBO that combines the copula log-likelihood (log c(Q_1,…,Q_M) + Σ_m log f_m) with the task loss, and is theoretically grounded by Sklar’s theorem ensuring a unique joint for continuous marginals. This end-to-end alignment improves AUROC/AUPR over strong baselines on matched multimodal MIMIC datasets."},{"problem":"In real-world settings, one or more modalities are often missing; naive imputations (zeros/means) ignore marginal distributions and joint dependencies, harming downstream performance.","method":"CM2 treats the learned marginal GMM of each modality as a generator to impute missing modality embeddings by sampling z_m ~ F_m in the latent space under a MAR assumption. Because the copula parameter α is learned jointly, the marginals encode cross-modal dependence, yielding pseudo-embeddings that better reflect the joint structure. A reparameterized mixture sampler (GPS) supports training-time imputation, and the imputed features are fused via a 2-layer LSTM and MLP classifier. Experiments on partially matched MIMIC datasets show consistent gains over baselines, with ablations confirming the benefits of copula alignment and GPS."},{"problem":"Classical copula inference (e.g., MCMC) is computationally prohibitive for high-dimensional deep multimodal learning.","method":"CM2 employs stochastic variational inference with a factorized variational family over modality marginals (densities q_m and CDFs Q_m), deriving an ELBO that aggregates task-specific loss and copula-based joint likelihood. The copula parameter α and GMM parameters (μ, Σ) are optimized via backpropagation, using a tractable approximation to multivariate Gaussian CDFs and diagonal covariances to enable reparameterization. This scalable optimization supports large MIMIC cohorts and standard backbones (ResNet34, LSTM, TinyBERT), maintaining robustness across different copula families."}]}
